title: For Sale:  1903 Springfield Mark 1
postcontent: This is an excellent condition 1903 Mark 1 Springfield 30-06.  It dates to 1919 and is a Mark 1 meaning it was built for the Pederson device having an ejection port on the left side of the receiver. A rarer version of the 1903 that was only made between 1919 and 1920.  The stock has all original cartouches and has no issues, no dents, no cracks, ect. This rifle was sent to the Rock Island Arsenal for rebuild in June of 1944.  The barrel was replaced and is dated with the flaming bomb.  I don't believe it was issued after arsenal rebuild as the bore is perfect; shiny and sharp lands in the rifling.  The rifle even has the issue cleaning kit in the buttstock.  Available at extra cost are the bayonet and ammo belt.  These are very collectable.  The bayonet is a Model 1905 made by Springfield Arsenal in 1906. It is in excellent condition and has a USN marked Mark 1 scabbard from WWII and is available for $150.  The ammo belt is a Model 1923 belt issued from '42 to '44.  It is designed to hold the 1903 stripper clips or the Garand Enbloc clips. It is in good condition as all snaps work, no tears, holes ect.  and includes twenty stripper clips for $100.  I would take $1050 for everything.  I will consider trades in firearms in partial trade or LIKE value.  Call or text 221-8781

title: For Sale:  Rare Limited Production Smith and Wesson Airlite Ti  Model 332, 32 H&R Magnum
postcontent: UPDATE:  SMITH AND WESSON CONFIRMED THIS MORNING THROUGH MY SERIAL # THAT THIS REVOLVER IS INDEED THE RARE MODEL 332, AND THAT IT HAD A PRODUCTION DATE OF 12/11/2000 This is a rare and valuable Smith and Wesson Airlite Ti (the "Ti" is for the titanium cylinder).  It's a J-frame, 6 shot revolver chambered in 32 H&R magnum.  I've had it for about 15 or 16 years, maybe it's even been 17 years.  I'm the original purchaser, I bought it at a gun shop in Miami Florida, but I just cant recall exactly which year I acquired this.  It was produced for only a limited time between 1999 and 2003, after which it was discontinued in 2004.  I'm pretty sure I acquired it around 1999 -2000 when I was still very early in my career,  but I'm waiting for Smith and Wesson to confirm that for me by the serial number. This was one of my backup pocket guns all these years, and to be totally candid, I was a bit shocked and surprised (pleasantly so) to discover this week through my research, that this was actually a valuable and pricey little gun for a pocket revolver.  I really had no idea frankly, and  had I known, I would have at least dusted it off and taken a better picture of it than I did :). I literally pulled it out of my pocket with all its built up pocket lint  and dust and fingerprints, and just snapped a quick pic, thinking this was probably just a $200 used gun.  But amazingly,  these things routinely sell for over $ 1,000 I've since learned.  Funny thing is I've always had a love hate relationship with this thing.  What I loved was that it was SUPERLIGHT thanks to the titanium cylinder, and carried 6 shots instead of 5, and was a nice smooth low recoil shooter.  What annoyed me was that sometimes spent cases tend to stick, and you have to poke them out with a pen or something.  SO anyway, Ive had this for all this time, it probably looks a bit rougher than it is bc I didn't bother to pretty it up at all before photographing it.  But it's actually seen very little actual use and has been shot not that much, it's just been carried a lot. Doubt if I have more than 250-300 rounds thru this thing, if that.  As for asking price, I'm going to wait until I hear from Smith and Wesson first on my purchase date, but I will entertain offers until then.  In the meantime, I'll wipe it down and take a cleaner pic. The Riverside Arms Co. name first appears in the J. Stevens Arms & Tool Co., Chicopee Falls, Mass., catalogue No. 54 issued circa 1914 on a hammerless double the No. 315 and a hammer double No. 215. These guns were based on G.S. Lewis Patents No. 1,086,378 granted Feb. 10, 1914, for the hammer gun and Patent No. 1,136,247 granted Apr. 20, 1915, for the hammerless gun. During WW-I the Stevens factories were taken over by, I believe New England Westinghouse, for wartime production. After the Great War the Chicopee Falls factories were bought by Savage Arms Corp. and the gun business there emerged as J. Stevens Arms Co. a wholly owned subsidiary of Savage Arms Corp. They continued to manufacture both Stevens and Riverside guns up to about 1930, when they changed the name of their lower priced line from Riverside Arms Co. to Springfield Arms Co.

The new blow-back operated 9mm UZI PRO incorporates advanced polymers in the lower section of the receiver resulting in lighter weight and relocation of the magazine release to a more practical and traditional pistol based location. title: For Sale:  ITALIAN CARCANO RIFLE 6.5X52MM
postcontent: The standard Italian rifle of the Great War was adopted in 1891. It was fed with a 6-round clip. The clip was a Mannlicher design and the breech block assembly was designed by an Italian gunsmith named Carcano. While it is looked down upon by some devotees of the "finer" rifles, it was a rugged weapon that didn't foul up easily and withstood hard treatment. Its smaller cartridges [Cal. 6.5x52 mm vs. 7.92 mm Mauser] meant a soldier could carry more rounds and its clip held 6 rounds vs. 5 per clip for almost all rifles of the other belligerents. It's length [140 cm, 160 cm with the bayonet] was designed for an obsolete method of warfare, allowing an infantryman to fend off the lance or saber of a mounted cavalryman. Since it proved to be clumsy in the tight confines of the trenches, a carbine version called the 'moschetto' adapted from the carbine version used by the cavalry was also given to special troops, carabinieri [MP's], officers, NCOs and Arditi [shock troops]. Both carbines fired the same cartridge the rifle did, indeed they were just shortened versions of the rifle. Both had a turned down bolt handle rather than a straight one. The cavalry version had a built in folding bayonet while the infantry adaptation had a detachable one and a longer wood stock.

title: For Sale:  Law Professional 7mm
postcontent: If you are looking for the ultimate lightweight rifle, look no further. A fluted barrel and bolt body, along with a lightweight Legendary Arms Works Stock makes The Professional easy to carry over the roughest terrain. The removable muzzle brake makes it a pleasure to shoot. Let’s not forget about accuracy; these guns were designed for superior accuracy for that mountain-to-mountain shot.Features:Each Legendary Arms Works Professional Rifle includes:LAW model 704 action, Controlled Round FeedHoned, stainless steel, fluted barrel with removable muzzle brake and thread protectorCustom tuned Timney triggerThree position safetyLegendary Arms Works (formerly High Tech Specialties) hand laid fiberglass stock with aluminum bedding blocks for added strength and accuracy.A 1” Pachmayr Decelerator recoil padCustom one piece aluminum trigger guard, inside the trigger bow releaseTactical Grey(H-227Q) Cerakote (TM) metal finish for the ultimate protectionTri-Color OD Green speckle paint stock colorUnmatched accuracy, Lifetime warrantyWeight: 6.6 lb – 7.0 lbThe 7mm Remington Magnum rifle cartridge was introduced as a commercially available round in 1962, along with the new Remington Model 700 bolt-action rifle. It is a member of the belted magnum family that is directly derived from the venerable .375 H&H Magnum. The original purpose of the belted magnum concept taken from the .300 H&H and .375 H&H, was to provide precise headspace control, since the sloping shoulders, while easing cartridge extraction, were unsuitable for this purpose. Improved cartridge extraction reliability is desirable while hunting dangerous game, which would be of concern when needing a fast follow up shot. The 7mm Rem is based on the commercial Winchester .264 Win Mag, .338 Win Mag, and .458 Win Mag, which were based on the same belted .300 H&H and .375 H&H cases, trimmed to nearly the same length as the .270 Weatherby Magnum.The 7mm Remington Magnum offers ballistics better than the .30-06 Springfield with bullet weights of 175 grains and less, one of the more popular loads being a 160 grain spitzer loaded to 3,000 ft/s (910 m/s). This is due both to the higher muzzle velocity of the magnum compared to the Springfield and that .284 diameter bullets tend to have better ballistic coefficients than .308 diameter bullets of comparable mass. It is arguable that the 7 mm Remington Magnum offers marginally better ballistics with 175 grain bullets, the heaviest bullet commonly used in the caliber. The .30-06 Springfield can, however, be loaded with heavier bullets up to 220 grains.
